Artie is a good storyteller, but also an untrustworthy bullshit artist. This is the second story I've checked out because it sounded like awesome stuff, but it turns out too good to be true. He's hooked on being the best so-called clean rocknroll comic at AA. But one's best jokes shouldn't be lies about internationally broadcasted stuff that can easily be verified. That's not how fictionalisation works. It ruins the jokes afterwards.
Artie's punchlines are well crafted jokes about the sadness of his imploded life, but easily instantly exposed.
He didn't puke right when rosanne mentioned her bathing suit. He just puked during a radio show.
And giraldo didn't call him a "fat f*cking drug addict" and didn't do the hands thing, so artie wasn't humoristically betrayed by his druggy friend he just saved and who would die soon afterwards anyway.

Funny how that works. One learns in comedy courses to spin one's actual real life anecdotes into "material". There's an unspoken pact between comedians to accept everyone's is just pretending to share authentic life stories while telling timed fiction. And the pact with the audience is that they don't question truth but accept it as something entertaining between fiction and nonfiction, in order to get caught up, to identify and to be touched (and escape). But this game of mirrors doesn't work any more, for me at least, when the material is based on already famously shared moments, that can also easily be traced back. I guess artie's old school junky jokes outdate the surveilling foreverness of the Internet. Luckily they fit the simplistically dumbed down mass media short attention span of current times.
